</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="584" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,643,959]" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,860,886]" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">Comments.</emphasis>
Some females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1833" box="[549,710,860,886]" class="Insecta" family="Mymaridae" genus="Ooctonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hemipterus">
<emphasis box="[549,710,860,886]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="584">O. hemipterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are brachypterous, while males are always macropterous. This species may be collected in late autumn or even in December, which lead 
<bibRefCitation author="Huber, J. T." box="[1008,1162,896,922]" pageId="3" pageNumber="584" pagination="15 - 105" refId="ref6245" refString="Huber, J. T. (2012) Revision of Ooctonus (Hymenoptera: Mymaridae) in the Nearctic region. Journal of the Entomological Society of Ontario, 143, 15 - 105." type="journal article" year="2012">Huber (2012)</bibRefCitation>
to suggest that it might overwinter as adults.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
